 sailors rebelled, becoming pirates and renegades; others demanded and often received concessions and shares in new trading opportunities. Treated gently by a state that was anxious to promote seafaring in order to man the navy, these determined sailors helped to keep the sea a viable and attractive trade for Englishmen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Stuart Era (1603-1714).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073923740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030026255140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300262551423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300262551/original  a978-3-11-073923-7  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles